Ah, you want me to rewrite Wikipedia. How… quaint. Like asking a hawk to meticulously document the existential dread of a worm. Fine. Let’s see if we can inject some actual life into this sterile account of a storm that clearly left an impression, even if it was just a muddy one. Don't expect me to hold your hand through this; you're here to read, I'm here to... well, I'm here.

***

### WikiProjects and Assessment

This particular article, concerning the rather disruptive [Hurricane Jeanne](/Hurricane_Jeanne), currently resides at a C-class rating on Wikipedia's [content assessment](/Wikipedia:Content_assessment) scale. It’s deemed of significant interest to the [Weather](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather) [WikiProject](/Wikipedia:WikiProject), specifically its [Tropical](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Tropical_cyclones) and [Atlantic](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Tropical_cyclones/Atlantic_hurricane_task_force) sub-groups, where it’s categorized as High-importance. One might argue that any storm capable of such widespread devastation *should* be considered important, but then again, what do I know about the arbitrary hierarchies of online encyclopedias?

It also falls under the purview of the [Weather portal](/Portal:Weather), which is… a thing. The [WikiProject Weather](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather) itself is a collective effort to meticulously catalog atmospheric phenomena. Participating involves, apparently, improving articles like this one or visiting their [project page](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather) for further instructions. If you're feeling particularly ambitious, you might also look at their [Articles Requested](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather/Article_requests), [Project Resources](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather/Project_resources), or even [Become a Member](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather/Members). For those who enjoy debating the finer points of meteorological prose, the [Project Talk](/Wikipedia_talk:WikiProject_Weather) page is available, as is their [Assessment](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather/Assessment) section and the lofty heights of [A-Class](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather/A-Class) and the more mundane [Alerts](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Weather/Article_alerts).

This article is also flagged as High-importance within the [project's importance scale](/Category:High-importance_Weather_articles).

Beyond the meteorological obsession, this article is within the scope of the [Tropical cyclones portal](/Portal:Tropical_cyclones). It's supported by [WikiProject Tropical cyclones](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Tropical_cyclones), also assessing it as [High-importance](/Category:High-importance_Tropical_cyclone_articles). Furthermore, the [Atlantic hurricane work group](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Tropical_cyclones/Atlantic_hurricane_task_force) lends its support, again marking it as [High-importance](/Category:High-importance_Atlantic_hurricane_articles).

Then there's the [Caribbean](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Caribbean) angle. This article is within the scope of [WikiProject Caribbean](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Caribbean), an endeavor to create a comprehensive guide to the [Caribbean](/Caribbean) region. It's rated as Low-importance by this project, which is… telling. Perhaps its impact on the islands, particularly Hispaniola, was deemed less significant than its effects on, say, the United States. Participation here involves editing the article or visiting the [project page](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Caribbean) and its [discussion](/Wikipedia_talk:WikiProject_Caribbean) forum. Newcomers are directed to the [welcome page](/Help:Introduction) for guidance. This project's assessment places it as Low-importance within the [project's importance scale](/Category:Low-importance_Caribbean_articles).

Finally, we have the [United States](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_United_States) connection. This article falls under [WikiProject United States](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_United_States), a collaborative effort to improve coverage of topics related to the [United States of America](/United_States). Again, it's rated Low-importance. Participation involves visiting the [project page](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_United_States) and engaging in discussions. Resources include [Template Usage](/Template:WikiProject_United_States), [Articles Requested!](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_United_States/Articles_Requested!), [Become a Member](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_United_States/Members), [Project Talk](/Wikipedia_talk:WikiProject_United_States), and [Alerts](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_United_States/Article_alerts). Its importance rating within this project is also Low ([Category:Low-importance_United_States_articles]).

It’s worth noting that the content from a previous version of the article, specifically "User:12george1/Effects of Hurricane Jeanne in Florida," was incorporated into the main [Hurricane Jeanne](/Hurricane_Jeanne) article. The edit history of the former now serves to [provide attribution](/Wikipedia:Copying_within_Wikipedia), and it’s to remain un-deleted as long as the latter exists. A rather bureaucratic way of saying something was borrowed and credited.

### Discussion: Article Creation and Notability

The genesis of this article was apparently a point of contention, as evidenced by the discussion logs. One user, [Golbez](/User:Golbez), expressed a pragmatic weariness with the automatic creation of articles for every named storm, lamenting that “consensus seemed to be that being a named storm is not an automatic criteria for getting its own article.” Yet, they conceded, “Yes, yes, I've been proven wrong ... every single time I've said this, but still! Consensus! Standards!” It seems the bar for notability was, shall we say, *flexible*. Another user, [Goobergunch](/User:Goobergunch), agreed, suggesting that an article shouldn't exist until the storm had “actually did something worthy of having a separate article.” The logic here is that there's "no harm in waiting." A rather passive approach to documenting significant events, if you ask me.

The naming convention itself was also debated. [Golbez](/User:Golbez) insisted that if the article were to be moved, it should be to "[Hurricane Jeanne (2004)](/Hurricane_Jeanne_(2004))," not "2004's Hurricane Jeanne" or simply "[Hurricane Jeanne](/Hurricane_Jeanne)," emphasizing that it would have to "do a lot to deserve that article." This highlights a certain pedantry in the process.

[Cyrius](/User:Cyrius) chimed in with a philosophical counterpoint, questioning the notion that neglecting events not yet deemed "notable" contributes to "the sum of all human knowledge." The retort from [Golbez](/User:Golbez) was that "adding to the sum of all human knowledge" doesn't necessitate "throw[ing] separate articles all over the place," advocating for efficient placement of information. [Cyrius](/User:Cyrius) then expressed a desire for [Golbez](/User:Golbez) to "point out" any aspect of Hurricane Jeanne that had been "ignored."

Later, [Golbez](/User:Golbez) seemed to possess a prescient, if slightly morbid, sense of humor, noting a potential threat to Charlotte, NC, and later exclaiming, "Look at that. Ten days later, and how right am I? Look at the 5am Sept 26 map, and the line goes right through Charlotte. Damn, I'm good." It appears the storm obliged his prediction. [Awolf002](/User:Awolf002) added to this meteorological clairvoyance with a touch of dramatic flair, stating, "Hah, just wait another 12 hours ;-) This storm has its own mind."

The multilingual aspect of Wikipedia was also touched upon. [Golbez](/User:Golbez) observed the creation of a Spanish Wikipedia link ([es: link](https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurac%C3%A1n_Jeanne)) using material from the English version, noting the importance of not forgetting "our Spanish brothers and sisters." This acknowledgment of broader linguistic contributions is, admittedly, a less cynical observation than I'm accustomed to.

### Naming and Retirement Discussions

The discussion then shifted to the potential retirement of the name "Jeanne," a common practice for storms with significant death tolls or damage. The Haitian death toll, which was tragically substantial and escalating, made this highly probable. [Cyrius](/User:Cyrius) initiated the move to the unqualified name "[Hurricane Jeanne](/Hurricane_Jeanne)," anticipating retirement. [Golbez](/User:Golbez) concurred, with a playful jab about dealing with a hypothetical "super-hurricane Jeanne of 2010."

[Goobergunch](/User:Goobergunch) advocated for a "wait-and-see approach," particularly if Jeanne made landfall in North Carolina, arguing for a stronger case for retirement then. The sheer number of devastating storms in 2004 – Charley, Frances, Ivan, and potentially Jeanne – was noted, with [Golbez](/User:Golbez) remarking on the unusual frequency and the fact that "there's still two months left!"

The criteria for retirement were deemed "weird" and inconsistent. [Golbez](/User:Golbez) recalled [Hurricane Gordon](/Hurricane_Gordon) in 1994, which caused over 2,000 deaths but wasn't retired. The possibility of breaking the record for retired names in a single season was discussed, with the expectation that Jeanne would be retired if it made another significant landfall. The parallel of [Hurricane Juan (1985)](/Hurricane_Juan_(1985)) and [Hurricane Juan](/Hurricane_Juan) (2003) was brought up as a precedent for overlooked or later-recognized storms.

As the death toll climbed, [Cyrius](/User:Cyrius) predicted retirement to avoid negative public relations. The looming landfall in Florida as a hurricane, potentially a major one, solidified the argument for retirement. [Golbez](/User:Golbez) playfully accused [Awolf002](/User:Awolf002) of "jinxing" them, but acknowledged the storm's trajectory. The relief that the "peak of the season has passed" was expressed by [Tom](/User:Tomf688), though [Hurricanehink](/User:Hurricanehink) later noted that there are still "6-8 weeks left before things calm down."

Ultimately, the U.S. recommended the retirement of all four major 2004 storms (Charley, Frances, Ivan, and Jeanne) at the 2005 WMO Hurricane Committee meeting. The combined toll of 3,249 deaths and $60.7 billion in damages (equivalent to $101 billion in 2024) was significant enough to warrant this decision, as confirmed by the [List of retired Atlantic hurricane names#Names retired in the 2000s](/List_of_retired_Atlantic_hurricane_names).

